The top stories covered by The National Desk in 2023

by JACKSON SINNENBERG | The National Desk

Mon, December 25th 2023 at 11:15 AM
Updated Mon, December 25th 2023 at 11:37 AM
70
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
Former President Donald Trump's legal woes, the Chinese spy balloon, the disappearance of the OceanGate Titan submersible and a year of infighting amongst House Republicans were all among the most popular and important stories The National Desk covered in 2023 (from clockwise). (Photos courtesy of the Fulton County Sheriff's Office, Chad Fish via AP, OceanGate Expeditions via AP, and AP Photo/Jose Luis Magana.)

WASHINGTON (TND) — The word ‘unprecedented’ gets thrown around a lot – probably too much – in the era of the 24-hour news cycle, yet it is hard to think of another word to describe the top stories The National Desk covered over the year. That especially applies to the news about our national politics.

For the first time in history, a former President of the United States was charged with a crime: first multiple at the state-level and then by the government he, Donald Trump, once led. The presumptive 2024 Republican nominee for president racked up 91 counts, to all of which he has pleaded “not guilty,” across three states and the District of Columbia.

Congress’ recent track record of infighting reached new heights as the constant waring between factions in the House Republican Conference led to bitter battles throughout the year over the group’s direction and leadership.

Add on Israel suffering its own 9/11 in October and the political, social, and cultural fallout the Hamas terror attack inspired in the U.S. and its already a dizzying year.

But in between the big political headlines were stories of personal tragedy, natural disasters and more.

Here’s the year in stories, if you missed any.

JANUARY

The year began with a pair of national shocks right out of the gate. Barely two days into the new year, millions of Americans watched in horror as they witnessed Buffalo Bills’ Safety Damar Hamlin collapse on the field in Cincinnati during a Monday Night Football broadcast of the Bills versus the Bengals. Hamlin was given CPR on the field and rushed to a local hospital, where doctors said he suffered a heart attack following a tackle. Hamlin received an outpouring of support from the league – which suspended the game and rescheduled it – and fans, who helped raise over $3.5 million for his Christmas toy drive in the hours following his accident. The incident ignited discussions around the health of contact-sport athletes like football players as doctors and health care experts used Hamlin’s collapse to emphasize the importance of CPR training as well as the risks that the kind of aggressive tackle he received – with doctors saying the kind of blunt-force trauma to the chest set of the cardiac arrest. After being released from the hospital in Cincinnati nearly a week later, Hamlin returned to Buffalo to continue to recover, and was spotted cheering on his teammates at home games until he was cleared to play in April and resumed full practice with the team in July.

The second shock to the nation came a day after Hamlin’s collapse, when House Republican leader Kevin McCarthy failed to be elected Speaker of the House on the first ballot, the first time in 100 years that such an event occurred. McCarthy was denied the office second in-line for the presidency by a block of, initially, about 20 hardline, right-wing members of the Republican conference – mostly members of the Freedom Caucus – who expressed reservations over the leader’s moderate record. The battle stretched across the entire week, ending on the 15th ballot cast in the wee hours of Saturday, Jan. 7, becoming the longest fight for the speakership since 1860 (until the one following McCarthy’s ouster in October). McCarthy made many concessions to the holdouts, including prominent committee assignments and lowering the threshold to Motion to Vacate the Chair to one member (which would be Speaker McCarthy’s undoing). It would also be an augur for the House’s conduct for the rest of the year, marked by frequent infighting and controversy.

Jan. 7 also saw, after being delayed five days by the speaker fight, the swearing-in of one now former Rep. George Santos, R-N.Y., whose own saga would be fodder for headlines for 11 months.

FEBRUARY

The nation’s attention was pulled for a week in February to an unmanned aircraft that slowly drifted over the length of the continental U.S. – before it was shot down on Feb. 4 by an Air Force F-22 off the coast of the Carolinas. The Chinese Spy Balloon accelerated conversations around the nation about our increasingly strained relationship with the People’s Republic of China and the one-party state apparatus, the Chinese Communist Party. National Security experts raised the alarm after the balloon’s path took it over the home of U.S. Strategic Command and other bases that are known to house elements of the nuclear arsenal. While the balloon was found to have been equipped with capabilities to monitor sensitive communications, officials in the Biden administration told the Wall Street Journal that the devices were unlikely to have been able to transmit findings back to China.

The government declined to elaborate on that point. However, the incident certainly added gravitas and a greater sense of urgency to the first hearing held by the House Select Committee on the Chinese Community Party, which spoke to the ‘existential struggle’ between the CCP and the American system on Feb. 28, just barely three weeks since the balloon was shot out of the sky. “We may call this ‘strategic competition' but this is not a tennis match. This is an existential struggle for what life will look like in the 21st century,” Committee Chair Mike Gallagher, R-Wisc., as part of his opening statement. He further warned of the Chinese government’s desire to push a “techno-totalitarian surveillance state” model of rule across the globe. While many Republicans, and former President Donald Trump, cited the aerial incursion as an example of foreign policy weakness under President Joe Biden, the House Select Committee operated in strong bipartisan cooperation to discuss the rising threat.


However, hours after Americans could breathe a sigh of relief without the shadow of the Chinese spy balloon of Damocles hanging over them, the news of an explosion and apparent train derailment near the small community of East Palestine, Ohio would bring the nation’s collective attention down to earth. The night of Feb. 3, around 18 hours before the spy balloon was shot down, a freight train operated by Norfolk Southern derailed near East Palestine causing a collision between some of the train’s cars. Unfortunately, those cars were carrying a mix of hazardous chemicals and materials that ignited, some burning for days and others that seeped into nearby water systems and soil.

While the long-term environmental impact of the spill is yet to be known, the incident brought immediate attention to railway safety. Norfolk Southern and other major freight companies – who own and operate most of the tracks in the U.S. – were not aided in arguments that this was a one off due to a series of derailments that followed East Palestine in the coming weeks. The Senators from both Ohio and Pennsylvania sponsored a piece of legislation – the Railway Safety Act of 2023 – that would aim to substantially increase safety requirements for freight trains, especially those that carry hazardous materials. The bill will receive a vote on the Senate floor in the new year.

MARCH

After years of questions, investigations and claims of “witch hunt,” former President Donald J. Trump became the first president (ex or otherwise) to face criminal charges when a grand jury in New York indicted him on over 30 counts of violating state laws. The charges stemmed from hush money payments Trump arranged to be paid – through his attorney and fixer, Michael Cohen – to adult film star Stormy Daniels and former Playboy model Karen McDougal in the closing weeks of the 2016 election. Coming off the huge public backlash to the “Access Hollywood” tape, Trump is accused of seeking the women’s silence about affairs he had with both before his political career. Trump responded to the formal accusation with a regular battery of claims that the charges were the product of a “witch hunt” carried out by “radical left Democrats” to destroy him and the “‘Make America Great Again’ movement.” This indictment, handed down at the end of the month, would be the first of several to come over the year as the alleged misdeeds of his brief political career began to catch up to him.

Three days before Trump was indicted, the nation also saw one of the worst school shootings in recent memory, when three nine-year-old children and three adults were killed at The Covenant School in Nashville, Tenn. The tragedy sparked another fierce round of the perennial debate about gun violence and gun control – and related topics like public safety, gun access, mental health, and police presence in schools – in the U.S. The discussions around mental health and parents’ rights in school came to prominence in the immediate aftermath of the shooting as parents from the Covenant School sought to block the shooter’s – 28-year-old Aiden Hale, a transgender man who attended the school – manifesto from being released to the public out of concerns the writings would lead to further violence. While a judge ruled in favor of the parents in November, seven officers from the Nashville Police Department were found responsible for leaking images of the documents to the public. All have returned to regular duty and the Covenant School campus is set to resume operations in spring 2024.

APRIL

Only days after former President Trump was indicted by a New York grand jury, he arrived in his hometown and walked into a Manhattan court room to become the first president to be arraigned on criminal charges. He plead “not guilty” to 34 counts related to falsifying business records. The day’s events set a pattern for media coverage for the next three court appearances to come, as news helicopters traced Trump’s every move through the city, photographers burned through film and reporters unleashed a barrage of questions at the former president and his staff at every corner. While he was arrested – not the first president to be so – it would take four months for a proper mugshot to come. The scene in Manhattan was a circus unto itself, with major supporters like Reps. George Santos, R-N.Y., and Marjorie Taylor Greene, R-Ga., who compared Trump to Jesus and Nelson Mandela, joining the throngs of loyalists to decry the alleged witch hunt. He returned to his Mar-a-Lago resort that night – April 4 – to speak defiantly out against the charges and rally his supporters. Support indeed began pouring out for the ex-president, as his poll numbers began to rise in the wake of his first major court appearance of the year.

The fallout from the Covenant School shooting – and subsequent vehement debate about guns in the U.S. – made its way to the Tennessee House of Representatives during the first week of April. Two Black, Democratic lawmakers were expelled from the body by the Republican three-fourths majority over accusations they, and a white, female colleague, violated chamber rules and committed “disorderly conduct” by joining gun violence protesters with a bullhorn while they were in the room earlier in the week. The move against Reps. Justin Jones and Justin Pearson brought swift and forceful condemnation from the top of the Democratic party. Both were reinstated temporarily by local city officials in their districts before formally winning back their seats in special elections in August.

Another incident in April continued to fuel the fires of the resurgent gun debate when a Black teenager in Missouri was shot in the head after knocking at the door of the wrong house. Ralph Yarl, 16, was shot by 84-year-old Andrew Lester after the former mistakenly arrived at the latter’s house trying to pick up his younger twin brothers. Despite the head wound, Yarl, a gifted bass clarinetist, escaped and made a full recovery. Lester, whose grandson told CNN he often made “racist comments,” plead not guilty to charges related to the shooting in September.

MAY

The immigration debate and migrant crisis hit a new peak in the second week of May when the Biden administration allowed Title 42 to expire. That set of pandemic-era rules implemented by the Trump administration allowed the government to turn away migrants at the border, including asylum seekers, under the pretense of trying to prevent the spread of COVID-19. Migrants amassed at the U.S.-Mexico border in the days leading up to Title 42’s expiration on May 11 and began surging across in the policy’s waning hours, with communities like El Paso reporting nearly 2,000 individuals trying to cross illegally that day. The fallout for Biden, the Department of Homeland Security and both national parties was swift. Congressional Republicans ramped up their routine threats of political action against DHS Secretary Alejandro Mayorkas – Kevin McCarthy began raising the specter of impeachment in November 2022 – launching an investigation into his “dereliction of duty” at the border. Meanwhile moderate Democrats tried to join with Republicans to push for an extension of Title 42, but the effort fizzled. Numbers of illegal crossings have continued to rise – though they had been on an upward trend anyway in recent years – and immigration promises to be a major theme of the 2024 election.

Another crisis threatened to hit Washington and the nation at the end of the month, as Congress and the White House hurtled towards the deadline to lift the debt ceiling and the possibility of the U.S. defaulting on its debt for the first time in history. Months of stalled and stagnant negotiations between Speaker McCarthy and the president came to fruition over Memorial Day weekend as they announced a deal to raise the debt ceiling $4 trillion over the next two years in exchange for keeping government spending at current levels for that same period. After barely passing out of the House Rules Committee May 30, the House passed the bill the next day, despite protests from the hard right House Freedom Caucus that the bill did not go far enough. The Senate passed the bill the day after, June 1, allowing Biden to sign in time to avert a global financial catastrophe. However, the fight in the House left wounds between McCarthy and his right flank that would ultimately lead to his ouster in October.

Earlier in the month, Republican members of the House Oversight Committee, led by Rep. James Comer, R-Ky., presented a new report that alleged massive corruption by the president’s family and the president’s direct involvement in such dealings. However, fact checks of those and subsequent allegations have largely debunked Comer’s claims. Even normally sympathetic conservative news outlets have questioned Comer’s supposed facts.

JUNE

A week after the panic of debt ceiling fight, the nation was hit with a surprise political bombshell on the evening of June 8, when former President Trump announced via posts on his Truth Social platform that he had been indicted by the government over the "boxes hoax.” The Justice Department formally announced the grand jury indictment the next day – the first time in U.S. history a former president had been criminally charged by the government he once led – charging him with 37 counts of conspiracy and national security violations related to his alleged illegal retention of sensitive, top secret government documents following his departure from the Oval Office. Trump plead not guilty to the charges when he appeared in a federal courthouse in Miami the following Tuesday.

While the event inflamed conservative outrage and rhetoric over what they say is a “weaponization” of the Justice Department by Biden, some of Trump’s regular legal and political defenders began to turn on him here – notably his second Attorney General, Bill Barr. “I have been at his side defending against them when he is a victim. But this is much different,” Barr told Fox News two days before Trump’s Miami arraignment. “He is not a victim here. He was totally wrong that he had the right to have those documents.” Barr also called the charges “very damning.” While Trump would be federally indicted again in August, the documents case still represented an unprecedented event in U.S. history which carries still unknown legal and connotational questions for the nation moving forward.

However, other presidential-adjacent legal news hit headlines later in June as Hunter Biden formally entered a plea deal with U.S. attorneys in Delaware over tax crimes and lying about a firearms purchase. The deal, which fell apart the following month, was widely criticized by Republican lawmakers in Congress leading the investigation into the first son’s business dealings and dark years of addiction.

June continued its streak for unprecedented events when, after years of West Coast Americans dealing with the apocalyptic impact of wildfires, the East Coast was blanketed in smoke, harmful air and an eerie “Blade Runner”-esque orange glow as the burn off from Canadian wildfires drifted across the border. The on-and-off swells of smoke and harmful fumes triggered air quality alerts across June and July and delayed and even ground flights across the U.S. due to the impact on visibility conditions.

In further environmental disaster news that month, the world’s attention was focused for days on an area of the Atlantic Ocean near the R.M.S. Titanic’s final resting place after an OceanGate submersible went missing during a routine dive. While the news media reported for days on possible signs of life or hope for recovery over the week of June 18, the company announced on June 22 that the vessel and its five passengers were lost. Subsequent recovery efforts found that the vessel had catastrophically imploded due to the intense water pressure at the Titanic’s depth.

In a rare bright spot in the news cycle, members of the Jewish community in Pittsburgh received some closure after Robert Bowers, the shooter responsible for the Tree of Life Synagogue massacre in 2018, was found guilty of his crimes. The jury found him liable for all 63 counts with which he was charged – ranging from hate crimes and obstruction of religion freedom to murder – and later sentenced him to death for the deadliest attack on Jewish people in U.S. history. “I am grateful to God for getting us to this day," Rabbi Jeffrey Myers of the Tree of Life Congregation, who survived the attack, said in a written statement. "And I am thankful for the law enforcement who ran into danger to rescue me, and the U.S. Attorney who stood up in court to defend my right to pray."

JULY

Hunter Biden’s plea deal buckled in July after U.S. District Court Judge Maryellen Noreika’s scrutinized parts of the agreement that would have possibly given the first son blanket immunity in future prosecutions. Biden’s attorneys withdrew from the deal and subsequently entered a “not guilty” plea to the charges after federal prosecutors said plea would not include such immunity. In response, and due to mounting pressure from House Republicans over their own investigation into Biden, Attorney General Merrick Garland elevated one of the federal prosecutors in the case, U.S. Attorney David Weiss, to special counsel to continue the investigation with additional powers. Weiss’ appointment was met with criticism by conservatives in Washington, who viewed his five-years of investigating the first son as ineffective.

Around the same time as Biden’s plea deal fell through, Elon Musk finally followed through on a promise he made when he purchased Twitter to rebrand the website as “X.” It was the first step in Musk’s dream of creating an “everything” app called “X” – which he sees as the Western world’s answer to China’s WeChat.

The saga of mother-turned-conspiracy theorist and murderer Lori Vallow Daybell appeared to finally come to a public close in the final days of the month as well. After being found guilty of killing her two children and her ex-husband's current romantic partner, Daybell was sentenced to serve three consecutive life sentences. The convicted murderer claimed during the trial that her son and daughters were zombies, and she was a goddess sent to usher in the Biblical apocalypse, among other bizarre claims. She was extradited to Arizona in November to stand trial for a separate murder charge there.

July also saw another case of bizarre claims after Alabama native Carlee Russell claimed to have been kidnapped in an elaborate heist after going missing for two days. She claimed to have been taken from her car and held by a man against her will in various locations around Hoover, Ala. Her story failed to hold up under police questioning.

Lastly, following the Supreme Court striking down President Biden’s initial student debt relief plan at the end of their term in June, the president pushed for a new plan to forgive up to $39 billion in debt for some 800,000 borrowers. Biden said it would allow Education Secretary Miguel Cardona to "compromise, waive or release loans under certain circumstances."

AUGUST

Former President Trump was served a double legal whammy of the course of August, as the former reality TV star was hit with a second federal and second state indictment. A grand jury in Washington voted to charge Trump over his role in trying to overturn the 2020 election and alleged role in what some lawmakers call the “attempted coup” at the Capitol on Jan. 6, 2021.

The second case brought by Special Counsel Jack Smith – who also leads the investigation in the classified documents case – was dubbed by Attorney General Garland as “the largest investigation” in Justice Department history. He plead not guilty to the four charges – conspiracy to defraud the United States, conspiracy to obstruct an official proceeding, obstruction of, and attempt to obstruct an official proceeding, and conspiracy against rights – and continued to maintain that the indictments against him by Smith were “election interference.”

Only a couple of weeks later, the first presidential mugshot in history was captured when Trump appeared for his arraignment in Fulton County, Georgia, after a grand jury there charged him and 18 others in attempting to illegally overturn the 2020 election results in Georgia. Trump and his accused co-conspirators, which include close allies at the time of the election like White House Chief of Staff Mark Meadows, Rudy Giuliani, Sidney Powell and other attorneys, were prominently hit with racketeering charges under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) best known for being used to go after the Italian mafia and other organized crime groups.

Trump was personally charged with 13 counts – to all of which he plead “not guilty” – and will face a televised trial next year. While not the end of his legal troubles, as the Trump Organization faces a fraud trial and he personally faces a renewed defamation suit by writer E. Jean Carroll after he was found liable for defaming and sexually abusing her, Trump’s major legal cases do not resume until the new year.

At the outset of August, Congress was once again under enormous pressure from a looming deadline as the now-all-too-regular threat of a government shutdown. With hard right Republicans still sore over the debt ceiling fight, the House was barely able to scrape together a deal to keep the government funded for another 45 days while they hashed out a long-term deal. Those 45 would be Kevin McCarthy’s last as Speaker of the House.

Meanwhile, after wildfires devastated Canadian forests and choked cities with smoke across the lower 48 throughout early summer, the Hawaiian archipelago found itself engulfed in a roaring inferno for several days at the height of the summer. The blaze devastated large portions of the island of Maui, flattening whole neighborhoods and leaving at least 80 people dead. During a visit to the island near the end of the month, President Biden promised the government would help Maui “for as long as it takes” for its communities to recover.

In freak accident news, a house in Pennsylvania was reduced to an empty lot in mid-August after it suddenly exploded. The incident killed five people and caused damage to numerous other properties as debris from the blast rained down in the area. The local fire marshal said the house was known to have hot water tank issues.

SEPTEMBER

One month after David Weiss was appointed special counsel to investigate Hunter Biden, he unveiled a new round of felony firearms charges against the first son. Biden was charged with three counts: making a false statement in the purchase of a firearm; making a false statement related to information required to be kept by a federal firearms licensed dealer; and one count of possession of a firearm by a person who is an unlawful user of or addicted to a controlled substance. Biden is accused of purchasing the gun in 2018, at a time he admits he was addicted to crack cocaine. He appeared in court in October to enter a not guilty plea as his defense attorneys chalked up the charges as part of a political pressure campaign by Republicans who want to derail his father’s 2024 re-election campaign. In further Republican pressure, Weiss testified behind closed doors for nearly seven hours to the House Judiciary Committee in November over concerns from Chair Jim Jordan, R-Ohio, about how he was handling the Biden investigation.

Tragedy struck the roadways of the Empire State as kids got back to school in September after a Wayne Central School District school bus crashed along an intersection in upstate New York. Thankfully, none of the 22 high school students or three adults on the bus were killed – two were taken to the hospital – but the driver of a Toyota sedan than was hit by the bus after it served into its path did perish. The passengers on the bus were able to escape before it burst into flames.

OCTOBER

The total political, social, cultural, and human impact of Hamas’ Oct. 7 terror attacks on Israel – and the subsequent retaliatory war – and its global fallout will likely be unknown for decades. On that day, which became the deadliest day for Jews since the Holocaust, Hamas terrorists invaded the Jewish state by land, air, and sea, wantonly killing Israeli civilians, sexually assaulting women, burning villages to the ground and kidnapping Israeli and foreign hostages to be held in the Gaza Strip. While many Western nations leapt to Israeli’s aid on what became known as the country’s 9/11, the outbreak of armed conflict exacerbated the already contentious international debate over the geo-political future of Israel and Palestine to levels of unprecedent venom.

College students and other young activists around the U.S. praised Hamas’ actions as presidents of some of the U.S.’s most prestigious universities failed to condemn the alarming rise of antisemitism on their campuses (parallel to an explosion of anti-Jewish rhetoric across the country). Now in the third month of conflict, experts are questioning Israel’s objectives in its retaliatory campaign as thousands of Palestinians have been killed, the Gaza Strip lies in ruin, and the Israeli military faces intensifying scrutiny after it accidentally killed three hostages taken by Hamas.

Hamas’ surprise attack came after another shocking, earthshattering surprise in American political history when Kevin McCarthy became the first Speaker of the House to be forcibly removed from office after longtime critic Rep. Matt Gaetz, R-Fla., brought a successful “motion to vacate the chair” against the then-speaker. Gaetz, one of the main holdouts during McCarthy’s long path to the speakership in January, brought the motion against McCarthy after he worked with Democrats to pass an emergency 45-day stopgap measure to continue funding the government while the House worked on a long-term spending bill.

After McCarthy’s collaborations with Democrats on the debt ceiling and a similar spending bill in July, Gaetz and other colleagues had enough. "Instead of siding with his own party today, Kevin McCarthy sided with 209 Democrats to push through a continuing resolution that maintains the Biden-Pelosi-Schumer spending levels and policies," Rep. Andy Biggs, R-Ariz., wrote on X after the stopgap measure passed. Gaetz, Biggs and six other Republicans were joined by all the Democrats in formally voting McCarthy out.

In an era of Congress known for dysfunction, McCarthy’s removal from high office and the subsequent fight over a new speaker seemed to embody that dysfunctional ethos more than anything else this year. The House of Representatives spent three weeks without a speaker as Republicans fought internally over McCarthy’s successor. Moderates like Majority Whip Tom Emmer, R-Minn., and McCarthy’s otherwise heir apparent, Majority Leader Steve Scalise, R-La., were both defeated early in their quests for the gavel by Republican conference’s right flank. Archconservative Rep. Jim Jordan, R-Ohio, fought for the speakership across multiple ballots before stepping away due to continued opposition from a handful of Republican moderates. Rep. Mike Johnson, R-La., who came with his own round of political baggage, finally emerged as a consensus candidate near the end of the month and was unanimously elected to wield the gavel during the afternoon of Wednesday, October 25, 22 days after McCarthy’s ouster.

That same night, an already awful month got somehow even worse after Robert Card went on a shooting spree around Lewiston, Maine, killing 18 people and wounding 13 more in the deadliest mass shooting of 2023. Card, a former military-trained firearms instructor, had been committed to a mental health institution earlier in the year, was found dead two nights later. President and first lady Biden traveled to Lewiston the following week to grieve with and support the community.

NOVEMBER

As the 2023 calendar year wound down, House Republicans vamped up their investigation into President Biden’s family amidst their continued belief it was guilty of a vast criminal conspiracy. In November, the House Oversight Committee announced subpoenas for James Biden, one of the president’s brothers, and Hunter Biden. The committee members also requested James’ wife Sara and Hallie Biden, the widow of the president’s son Beau.

Hunter would somewhat honor the committee’s request in December when he arrived at the Capitol Dec. 13 demanding a public hearing after fighting with the committee for weeks, due to its desire for his testimony to be given behind closed doors. Rep. Comer, the committee chair, pushed for the new round of statements from the Biden family after claiming he had new evidence that the family’s bank records showed extensive tax evasion and a to Joe Biden from James when the former was out of office. A subsequent fact check revealed James was likely paying back a personal loan to his brother.

Meanwhile, the streak of unlucky on American motorways continued from September after a fiery crash on the Ohio highway led to the death and injury of two dozen people. On Nov. 14, a semi-truck rear-ended a charter bus carrying members of the Tuscarawas Valley High School, who were due to perform at the Ohio School Boards Association's annual convention. Two pedestrian vehicles also joined the pile-up, which later burst into flames. Three students and three adults were killed.

DECEMBER

House Republicans’ year of investigating the alleged crimes of the Biden family and potential high crimes and misdemeanors of President Biden reached a new level on Dec. 13 when the conference unanimously voted to formally open an impeachment inquiry into the Bidens. “Evidence uncovered has shown a very disturbing trend by the Biden family. We've spent months accumulating evidence,” Rep. Comer told reporters shortly after the vote. “We have a simple question I think an overwhelming majority of Americans have: What did the Bidens do to receive the tens of millions of dollars from our enemies around the world?”

However, as the National Desk’s Austin Denean wrote in the immediate aftermath of the vote, “Months of investigation and troves of documents and witness testimony, Republicans have yet to uncover concrete evidence showing the president committing wrongdoing.” The hope by Reps. Comer, Jordan and other leaders of the push to investigate the Bidens hope the formality of the impeachment inquiry will afford them new investigative powers to find that concrete proof.

Hunter Biden’s legal woes continued to mount as, despite claiming no wrongdoing, he was hit with another indictment in Special Counsel David Weiss’ investigation. In a now cross-country, bicoastal legal battle, the first son is facing nine charges – three felony, six misdemeanor – in California related to his failure to pay over $1.4 million in taxes between 2016 and 2020. The indictment alleges Biden spent the money on propping up a lavish and debaucherous lifestyle that included payments for “drugs, escorts and girlfriends, luxury hotels and rental properties, exotic cars, clothing, and other items of a personal nature, in short, everything but his taxes.”

On the other side of congressional year-end news, while ousted House Speaker Kevin McCarthy ultimately decided to leave Congress entirely after his fall from power, he did not leave alone. The embattled, controversial, and infamous Rep. George Santos, R-N.Y., became the sixth member in history to be formally expelled from the House of Representatives by his peers. The first-year member came to Washington on the heels of numerous reports that he fabricated most of his backstory and resume during his campaign. A House Ethics Committee investigation subsequently found “substantial evidence” that Santos had broken multiple laws, including campaign finance and election laws.

After the tumultuous year in national news and politics, prominently marked and divided by the news cycles around former President Trump’s legal woes, another legal first was added onto the 45th president’s plate. On the evening of Dec. 19, barely a week before Christmas, the Colorado Supreme Court announced it was barring Trump from appearing on the state’s ballot in the 2024 election. The ruling, which disqualifies him under the “insurrection clause” of the Constitution’s 14th Amendment, would ban him from the state primary ballot and discount any write-in votes made for him. Trump’s presumed opponent, President Biden, weighed in the following day, saying, “Now whether the 14th Amendment applies, I’ll let the court make that decision. But he certainly supported an insurrection. No question about it. None. Zero.”

The United States Supreme Court is likely to weigh in on the legal matter shortly, and likely that the 6-3 conservative majority will overturn it. However, in a year in which the legal challenges against Trump have spawned countless new legal and Constitutional questions, the Colorado Supreme Court’s decision seems like just one more on the pile.
